💧 Water Potability Prediction using Machine Learning

You can submit this for college or upload to GitHub as a report.

1️⃣ Introduction

Access to safe drinking water is essential for human health. Contaminated water can cause serious diseases and health issues. This project aims to build a Machine Learning model that predicts whether water is safe for drinking based on its chemical properties.

The model classifies water samples into:

Safe for Drinking (1)

Not Safe for Drinking (0)

2️⃣ Problem Statement

To develop a classification model that predicts water potability using physicochemical features such as pH, Hardness, Solids, Chloramines, Sulfate, Conductivity, Organic Carbon, Trihalomethanes, and Turbidity.

3️⃣ Dataset Description

The dataset contains water quality measurements with the following features:

Feature	Description
pH	Acidity/alkalinity level of water
Hardness	Capacity of water to precipitate soap
Solids	Total dissolved solids (ppm)
Chloramines	Amount of chloramines (ppm)
Sulfate	Amount of sulfates dissolved
Conductivity	Electrical conductivity of water
Organic_carbon	Amount of organic carbon
Trihalomethanes	Harmful disinfection by-products
Turbidity	Clarity of water
Potability	Target variable (0 = Not Safe, 1 = Safe)
4️⃣ Methodology
🔹 Step 1: Data Preprocessing

Checked missing values

Handled null values using mean/median imputation

Performed feature scaling using StandardScaler

Split data into training and testing sets (80/20)

🔹 Step 2: Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

Correlation heatmap

Boxplots to detect outliers

Distribution plots for feature analysis

🔹 Step 3: Model Building

The following models were implemented:

Logistic Regression

Decision Tree Classifier

Random Forest Classifier

🔹 Step 4: Model Evaluation

Models were evaluated using:

Accuracy Score

Confusion Matrix

Classification Report (Precision, Recall, F1-score)

5️⃣ Results

Random Forest performed better compared to other models.

Feature scaling improved model performance.

Some features showed weak correlation with potability.

